knowledge_graph.title: Provolone
knowledge_graph.description: Provolone is an Italian semi-hard cheese made from cow's milk. It is an aged pasta filata cheese originating in the Campania region, near Vesuvius, where it is still produced in pear, sausage, or cone shapes 10 to 15 cm long. Provolone-type cheeses are also produced in other countries.

related_questions.question: What is special about provolone cheese?
related_questions.snippet: Provolone is a semi-hard Italian cow's milk cheese that has a smooth texture and a mild smoky flavor. Provolone Cheese is made in two distinct varieties: Provolone Dolce and Provolone Piccante. Provolone Dolce is made using calf's rennet, aged approximately two to three months, and has a mild creamy and milky flavor.

related_questions.question: Is provolone just mozzarella?
related_questions.snippet: Flavor: Provolone has a much more complex flavor profile and sharper taste than mozzarella. Even provolone dolce, which is sweeter and milder, has a tangier flavor than mozzarella. Uses: Since provolone is a semi-hard cheese, and mozzarella is a semi-soft cheese, the two kinds of cheese have different uses.

buttons.snippet: What Does Provolone Cheese Taste Like? Provolone cheese can be anywhere from mild to sharp in flavor, depending on the age. Provolone Dolce, is sweet, and mild, while Provolone Piccante is buttery, sharp, and somewhat spicy.

buttons.subtitle: Origin Of Provolone
buttons.title: What is Provolone and how is it made? - Musco Food Corp.
buttons.snippet: Provolone originated in the Basilicata region, in southern Italy. However, its popularity soon outgrew this secluded region, resulting in a production throughout Italy, though concentrated in Lombardy and the Veneto region. Provolone falls under the category of “Pasta Filata” cheeses, e.g. “Stretched Curd”.
